<article>
    <h1>Beware The Belly Fat</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201113/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-13"><time>2020-11-13</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>A study done by the Na­tional Heart Cen­tre Sin­ga­pore in Au­gust this year found that Asians with di­a­betes and heart fail­ure who tend to gain weight around their mid­dle have a higher risk of poor hos­pi­tal­i­sa­tion out­comes. This is in com­par­i­son to pa­tients with di­a­betes and heart fail­ure in other groups, in­clud­ing the el­derly, the young and the obese. Fat around the tummy is vis­ceral fat that ac­cu­mu­lates around the or­gans, and is linked to greater in­sulin re­sis­tance.</p>
    <p>How­ever, with weight loss, vis­ceral fat is of­ten lost first, low­er­ing your risk of di­a­betes. Kick start a health­ier life­style by switch­ing to less-sugar op­tions li ke VITAGEN Less Sugar cul­tured milk drink. Con­tain­ing bil­lions of pro­bi­otics and added with pre­bi­otics that sup­port the growth of good bac­te­ria for a stronger de­fence against bad bac­te­ria and viruses, it is also for­mu­lated with real fruit juices and has eight times less white sugar than other milk cul­tured drinks in the mar­ket.</p>
    <p>Avail­able at all lead­ing hy­per­mar­kets, su­per­mar­kets, con­ve­nience stores and min­i­marts.</p>

